  "prompt": "Money laundering has to be illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime) appear legitimate by disguising its true source. Laws against money laundering are in place to combat criminal enterprises, protect the integrity of financial systems, and prevent the flow of illegal funds into the economy.\n\nMost countries have enacted specific anti-money laundering (AML) legislation and work with international organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) to set global standards and combat money laundering. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions are also required to report suspicious activities and implement measures to prevent money laundering.",
